          <div class = "section-a"> 
            <div class = "row">
              <div class = "col-md-8 col-md-offset-2" >
                <h3>Step 1: Prepare Your Questions</h3>
                <p><b>Compile relevant questions and answers.</b> Suggestions for sources include: </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Your own survey data!</li>
                  <li>Data from mainstream sources: reports and studies, census, literature reviews, media, government data.</li>
                  <li>Data from non-mainstream sources: community research, surveys, community experts, studies, etc.</li>
                </ul>    
                <p>Note: Data for questions and answers can be descriptive or numbers based. Questions can have any number of answers but most should have three or more answers. The number of questions created is dependant on the amount of time allocated for game play. Five to six questions should take about 20 minutes. Seven to eight questions should take about 30 minutes to complere. Keep in mind the time needed for post-game discussion (roughly 20 minutes).</p><br>
                <p><i class="fa fa-exclamation-triangle"></i><b>Tip:</b> Make the first question a warm-up question with multiple answers. Some questions have only one answer. Consider these as bonus questions where each team gets one chance to answer the question.</p><br>
                <p><b>Example Questions:</b>The Right to the City conducted a national study on the state of public housing in the United States. Part of the study included collecting secondary data on the public housing system. They used Data Feud in 8 cities to share that data back with residents and had a discussion about what the data was saying about their community. Below are samples of fomulated questions and answers based on their data. </p>
                <div class = "col-md-6" >
                  <b>1. When public housing units are demolished, what type of housing are those units replaced with?</b>
                  <ol>
                    <li>Housing/Section 8 vouchers (37%)</li>
                    <li>New public housing units (33%)</li>
                    <li>Market/Private rentals or put on sale (30%)</li>
                  </ol>
                </div>
                <div class = "col-md-6" >
                  <b>2. What are the themes/topics that come up the most often in newspaper articles about public housing in your city (Oakland)?</b>
                  <ol>
                    <li>Poor/Poverty (78)</li>
                    <li>Disrepair (45)</li>
                    <li>Gang (34)</li>
                    <li>Crime (34)</li>
                  </ol>
                </div>
              </div> <!--col 6 -->
            </div> <!--row  -->
          </div> <!--section a -->
          
          <div class = "section-b"> 
            <div class = "row">
              <div class = "col-md-8 col-md-offset-2" >
                <h3>Step 2: Create a Data Feud Game</h3>
                <ol>
                  <li><%= link_to "Create an account", signup_path %></li>
                  <li>Go to <%= link_to "My Games", current_user %> and click on the create a game button</li>
                  <li>Follow the on-screen instructions and enter your questions and answers</li>
                </ol> 
              </div> <!--col 6 -->
            </div> <!--row  -->
          </div> <!--section b -->
          
          <div class = "section-a"> 
            <div class = "row">
              <div class = "col-md-8 col-md-offset-2" >
                <h3>Step 3: Pre-game Setup</h3>
                <p><b>Assign Roles:</b> The game needs a <b>game operator</b> and <b>game-show host</b>. The game operator should practive simulating the game before the workshop. Both host and operator need to be familiar with the game play. 
                </p><br>
                <p><b>Print Multiple Answer-Keys:</b> If you already created an account and are logged in, you can print answer keys by going to <%= link_to "My Games", current_user %>, finding your game, and clicking "Print Answer Key" at the bottom of the game's description. Make enough copies to hand out to your audience, host, and game operator. Answer-keys are given out at the end of the game to help facilitate discussion.
                </p><br>
                <p><b>Prep for Post-Game Discussion (Optional):</b> We've detailed two options for a post-game discussion. <b>Option 1</b> allows participants to share their reactions to the data. <b>Option 2</b> dives into the differences between mainstream information and community information.
                </p><br>
                <div id="accordion">
                  <h3><i class="fa fa-caret-right"></i> Post-game Discussion: Option 1</h3>
                  <div>
                    <p><b>Sharing Reactions to the Data:</b> Data will be understood differently depending on who is the audience. In this activity, the participants will be asked to share their reactions to each question - deepening the collective experience.</p>
                    <p><i class="fa fa-clock-o"></i><b> Time needed:</b> 25 minutes</p>
                    <p><i class="fa fa-paperclip"></i><b> Materials needed:</b>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Post-its (as many post-its as there are	questions for each participant) </li>
                        <li>Butcher paper (as many sheets as there are questions)</li>
                        <li>Markers</li>
                        <li>Pens (for participants)</li>
                      </ul>
                    </p>
                     <p><i class="fa fa-tasks"></i><b> Post-game discussion setup (done before game begins):</b>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Hang the sheets of butcher paper in a visible place.</li>
                        <li>Number each sheet with a single number (one for each question in the game).</li>
                        <li>Pass out post-its to the participants. Each participant needs a post-it for each question of the game.</li>
                        <li>Have participants number each of their post-its sequentially to correspond with the number of the questions (e.g. 1-8 if there are 8 questions in the game).</li>
                      </ul>
                    </p>
                    <p><b>Leading the Discussion:</b> Once the game starts, after each question/round encourage the participants to write down their reaction to the information presented in a few short words on their post-it (e.g. What do they think of the data? It can be short like "no way!", "duh!", "surprising", "interesting", etc.).
                    </p>
                    <p>When the game is finished, go the answer key and review each of the questions again (if you've made any notes that provide additional information, share them now). With each question, have a couple of people share what they wront on their post-it. Ask them to elaborate on why they had that reaction.  
                    </p>
                    <p>Some guiding questions:
                    <ul>
                        <li>Is the answer what you expected?</li>
                        <li>Is there something in the data that surprised you?</li>
                        <li>How can this data apply to your work?</li>
                        <li>Have participants number each of their post-its sequentially to correspond with the number of the questions (e.g. 1-8 if there are 8 questions in the game).</li>
                      </ul>
                    </p>
                    <p>Now have everyone put their post-its on the corresponding numbered butcher paper. Let them spend a few minutes reading each other's responses. Allow time for questions and further discussion.  
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div id="accordion2">
                  <h3><i class="fa fa-caret-right"></i> Post-game Discussion: Option 2</h3>
                  <div>
                    <p><b>Community vs. Mainstream Info:</b> Often mainstream data differs from what is actually happening on the ground.  The game can be a tool to have discussion about this and lay the foundation for community research.</p>
                    <p><i class="fa fa-clock-o"></i><b> Time needed:</b> 15 minutes</p>
                    <p><i class="fa fa-paperclip"></i><b> Materials needed:</b>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Butcher paper</li>
                        <li>Markers</li>
                      </ul>
                    </p>
                    <p><i class="fa fa-tasks"></i><b> Post-game discussion setup (done before game begins):</b>
                      <ul>
                        <li>Hang butcher paper in a visible place.</li>
                      </ul>
                    </p>
                     <p><b>Leading the Discussion:</b> When dealing with mainstream data, have a note taker track the answers given by participants during the game – the 'incorrect' ones.  When reviewing the answer key, compare what was said by the participants versus what the mainstream data was.  
                      <ul>
                        <li>How is the data different?</li>
                        <li>What is the community information saying about this issue?</li>
                        <li>Why do you think the mainstream differs? Is it linked to a political agenda ignoring community experience?</li>
                        <li>Have participants number each of their post-its sequentially to correspond with the number of the questions (e.g. 1-8 if there are 8 questions in the game).</li>
                      </ul>
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
        
              </div> <!--col 6 -->
            </div> <!--row  -->
          </div> <!--section a -->
          
          <div class = "section-b"> 
